value.value: The flow of fluid from the nipple of the breast.
Gastroenteritis resulting from an infection with Campylobacter.
The degeneration and thinning of the epidermis and dermis. It is usually a manifestation of aging.
Abnormally high level of neutrophils in the blood.
Unintentional trauma to the body.
The manifestation of psychotic symptoms, such as hallucinations or delusions, in the presence of mania.

A laboratory finding indicating decreased number of hematopoietic cells in the bone marrow. It may result from decreased proliferation of all or part of the hematopoietic series (erythroid, myeloid, and megakaryocytic). Microscopically, the hematopoietic cells are replaced by adipocytes.
A laboratory test result indicating abnormally high numbers of megakaryocytes in the bone marrow.
A disorder that is related to pregnancy. Representative examples include ectopic pregnancy, toxemia of pregnancy, and gestational trophoblastic tumor.
A subtype of classic Hodgkin lymphoma with scattered Reed-Sternberg and Hodgkin cells in a diffuse or vaguely nodular mixed inflammatory background without nodular sclerosing fibrosis. (WHO, 2008)
Retinal damage resulting from diminished blood flow/oxygenation due to abnormalities of the retinal vessels.  Causes include hypertension, diabetes, thrombosis, embolism, and hemorrhage.
Nodular enlargement of the thyroid gland associated with hyperthyroidism.
The absence of the lens of the eye that is present at the time of birth.
A chronic, persistent inflammation of the glomeruli, which is slowly progressive, leading to impaired kidney function.
A group of viral illnesses that are vectored by mosquitoes, and that are characterized by increased susceptibility to bleeding diatheses.
Infection by Ancylostoma braziliense.
Infection of the prostate gland caused by Trichomonas vaginalis.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm that affects the uvula.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm that affects the mandible.
A subtype of classic Hodgkin lymphoma characterized by collagen bands that surround at least one nodule, and Hodgkin and Reed-Sternberg cells with lacunar type morphology. (WHO, 2008)
An intraepithelial carcinoma arising from any part of the digestive system without evidence of invasion.

label.value: Physiological Malfunction Arising from Mental Factor

value.value: A dysfunction in biological function that is due to a psychological process.

label.value: Musculoskeletal Malfunction Arising from Mental Factor

value.value: Physical symptoms or physiological abnormalities that have a psychological origin, and which are usually mediated through the autonomic nervous systems and do not involve tissue damage.

label.value: Skin Disorder Arising from Mental Factor

value.value: A skin disorder for which mental factors play a causative role.

label.value: Genitourinary Malfunction Arising from Mental Factor

value.value: A dysfunction in genitourinary function that is due to a psychological process.

A myelodysplastic/myeloproliferative neoplasm characterized by the presence of leukocytosis with increased numbers of neutrophils, promyelocytes, myelocytes, and metamyelocytes; blasts less than 20% in bone marrow and peripheral blood; dysgranulopoiesis; minimal or absent monocytosis; absence of eosinophilia; and presence of bone marrow hypercellularity with granulocytic proliferation and granulocytic dysplasia. Dysplasia in the erythroid and megakaryocytic lineages may be present or absent. No evidence of BCR/ABL fusion is present.

label.value: Endocrine Disorder Arising from Mental Factor

value.value: An endocrine disorder that is caused by abnormal mental function.

label.value: Adjustment Reaction with Prolonged Depressive Reaction

value.value: Temporary but prolonged and maladaptive depressive signs and symptoms associated with a life event.
A partial occlusion of the retinal artery.
A partial, temporary occlusion of the retinal artery.
An inherited form of retinal dystrophy.
Acute inflammation of the conjunctiva.
Conjunctivitis that is characterized by formation of a pseudomembrane.
Conjunctivitis that is persistent and long-standing.
Any non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder affecting the arteries, veins, or lymphatic vessels of the eyelid.
Discharge or drainage of fluid from the ear.

An anthracycline antineoplastic antibiotic isolated from the bacterium Actinomadura carminata. Carubicin intercalates into DNA and interacts with topoisomerase II, thereby inhibiting DNA replication and repair and RNA and protein synthesis.
A tumor mass composed of myeloblasts or immature myeloid cells.  It occurs in extramedullary sites or the bone.  (WHO, 2001)
Inflammation of the pericardium in acute rheumatic heart disease.
Inflammation of the endocardium in acute rheumatic heart disease.
Inflammation of the myocardium in acute rheumatic heart disease.
High blood pressure caused by renal artery stenosis.

Necrosis of the myocardium, as a result of interruption of the blood supply to the area. It is characterized by a severe and rapid onset of symptoms that may include chest pain, often radiating to the left arm and left side of the neck, dyspnea, sweating, and palpitations.
Documented history of previous myocardial infarction (MI), typically with objective evidence via positive biomarkers of myocardial necrosis.
The sudden onset of inflammation of heart muscle with myocellular necrosis; this is generally secondary to an infectious cause, and patients often have a recent history of a flu-like illness.
